## 4. What you might want to extend / customise

| Feature | Where to change |
|---------|-----------------|
| **Expose more fields** (e.g. packet comments, interface IDs) | Add them to the `frame` record in `pcapng.mli` and extend `caml_pcapng_frame_of_cpp`. |
| **Zero‑copy payload** | Instead of `caml_alloc_string` you could use a `Bigarray` that points directly to the C++ buffer (be careful with lifetime). |
| **Thread‑safe iteration** | Wrap the whole stub with `caml_c_thread_register` / `caml_release_runtime_system` as shown, but also protect the C++ iterator with a mutex if you plan to call `iter` from multiple OCaml threads. |
| **Error handling** | The stub currently maps any C++ exception to `Pcapng.Error`. You can add more specific exceptions (e.g. `Invalid_format`) by registering additional named values. |
| **Streaming mode** | Instead of loading the whole file at once, you could expose a `next : capture -> frame option` primitive that returns one frame at a time. |

Feel free to adapt the skeleton to the exact API of the real `libpcapng` library – the only part that is “mocked” above is the `pcapng::File` iterator; replace it with the real classes, keep the same shape of the stub, and you will have a production‑ready binding. Happy hacking!
